<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-246-156  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 246 156.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  May 1 1989 v6 n17 p1(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>SAA lineup means new game plan for IBM users. (Systems ApplicationArchitecture)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Chartoff, Marvin; Passmore, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>SAA is the key to cooperative processing in the IBM arena and hasfour components, the Common Communications Support (CCS), CommonUser Access (CUA), Common Programming Interface and CommonApplications.andP;  A key goal of SAA is to permit an applicationwritten on one hardware environment-operating system environmentto be ported easily to another.andP;  Important SAA CCS componentssupporting this processing model are the Common ProgrammingInterface for Communications (CPIC), Distributed Data Manager(DDM) and SQL.andP;  A key implication of SAA cooperative processing isthe move from 3270 dumb terminals to personal computer-basedintelligent workstations running the OS-2 Extended Editionoperating system.andP;  The planning process will involve changes tohardware and software, with the major challenge coming inrewriting applications.andP;  The challenges involved in convertingfrom the 3270-dominated application environment to a CPIC LU 6.2application environment are discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (products).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     SAASystem DesignNetwork ArchitectureEnhancementsStrategic PlanningSoftware MigrationNetwork ManagementConnectivity.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Workstation-to-mainframe configurations. (chart)SAA application migration. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>